      Chatham vs. ACA
   =20
 =20

A weird financial anomaly is that, in 2017 and 2018, the bonds of American =
Media Inc. started to trade at implausibly high prices. By late 2017, these=
 bonds were trading at lower yields than the bonds of Apple Inc., implying =
that AMI =E2=80=94=C2=A0the small, non-investment-grade publisher of the Na=
tional Enquirer =E2=80=94=C2=A0was a better credit than Apple. That seemed =
wrong. In 2018, AMI issued=C2=A0new=C2=A0bonds, at a much higher yield (10.=
5%) than the existing bonds, which also suggested that the prices of the ex=
isting bonds were wrong.
I remember that, at the time, this was a thing that people talked about. Bo=
nd trading prices are public, and you could see the prices of AMI bonds goi=
ng crazy. Some bonds were trading at obviously wrong prices, for a long tim=
e: What gave? The obvious assumption was that someone was doing market mani=
pulation, and it was easy to speculate about who: Chatham Asset Management,=
 the hedge fund firm that owned most of the bonds.
It was harder to figure out=C2=A0why. If Chatham was=C2=A0manipulating the =
market, by trading AMI bonds back and forth with itself at ever-higher pric=
es, what was it hoping to gain? Surely nobody=C2=A0else=C2=A0would buy thos=
e bonds from Chatham at the inflated prices: This is not a meme stock, it w=
as a small market with sophisticated investors, and nobody else would just =
look at the tape and say =E2=80=9Coh sure if these bonds trade at 110 I gue=
ss I=E2=80=99ll pay 110 for them.=E2=80=9D
Eventually, last April, the US Securities and Exchange Commission  brought =
a case against Chatham for =E2=80=9Cimproper trading of certain fixed incom=
e securities,=E2=80=9D and Chatham settled by paying $19 million. We   talk=
ed about this case at the time, and it did provide a more or less satisfact=
ory explanation of what was going on:
=09Yes, the AMI bonds were trading at silly prices because someone was trad=
ing them back and forth with itself at inflated prices.=09Yes, it was Chath=
am.=09The=C2=A0reason=C2=A0for this manipulation was, as these things go,=
=C2=A0fairly=C2=A0innocent: Chatham really liked the bonds, it owned a ton =
of them, but it owned them in several different funds, and sometimes those =
funds saw withdrawals or bumped up against limits on how many AMI bonds the=
y could own. Chatham=E2=80=99s management loved the bonds, though, so when =
one of its funds had to sell them, it would sell them to another of its fun=
ds that could still hold them. Each time, it would sell them at a somewhat =
higher price, so the price kept going up. This did have the effect of makin=
g more money for Chatham (it got paid based on assets and performance, and =
as the bonds kept going up it earned about $11 million of extra fees), but =
that doesn=E2=80=99t seem to have been its=C2=A0motivation. It just liked t=
he bonds and wanted to keep them, and the most convenient way it found for =
keeping them was by selling them to itself at ever-increasing prices.

So, right, that was an=C2=A0explanation, but it was kind of a dumb one? It =
makes sense that Chatham would need to sell the bonds from one fund and tha=
t it would want to buy them in another fund. But why trade them at ever-inc=
reasing prices? That=C2=A0answer is not especially satisfying.=C2=A0The fac=
t is that there was not much of a market for these bonds outside of Chatham=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0it owned most of them and mostly had to trade with itself =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0and so there really wasn=E2=80=99t some easily determined fa=
ir-market value for the bonds.
So Chatham would sell the bonds to a broker,
  [1]
=C2=A0and then buy them back from the broker (in a different=C2=A0fund) a d=
ay or so later. The brokers=C2=A0could=C2=A0have tried to buy and sell the =
bonds at fair-market prices =E2=80=94=C2=A0they could have analyzed the cre=
dit and said =E2=80=9Cwell based on the trading prices of comparable compan=
ies=E2=80=99 bonds, these bonds should be worth about 85 cents on the dolla=
r, so we=E2=80=99ll pay you 84.5 for them or sell to you at 85.5=E2=80=9D =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0but, for thinly traded risky bonds, that would have been tou=
gh, and the brokers knew that Chatham would buy them back anyway. (Because =
Chatham told them it would.) So instead Chatham would just call a broker=C2=
=A0up and say =E2=80=9Chey buy these bonds from us at 90,=E2=80=9D and the =
broker would, and then a day later it would call the broker back and say =
=E2=80=9Cokay we want those bonds back, we=E2=80=99ll pay you 90.5,=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0so the broker could make a little commission for doing this.
  [2]

And apparently Chatham never thought to sell the bonds (to itself!) for les=
s than it paid for them: It just based each trade=E2=80=99s price on the bo=
nd=E2=80=99s trading history, which meant its own previous trades, which in=
volved markups for the brokers. So=C2=A0next=C2=A0time it would call the br=
oker and sell for 90.5 and buy back for 91, etc., and eventually the prices=
 got comically high.
Anyway this is not allowed, you are supposed to trade at real market prices=
, etc. In some sense it is a little complicated to explain=C2=A0why=C2=A0th=
is is not allowed.=C2=A0The  SEC=E2=80=99s complaint says it violated rules=
 against =E2=80=9Cengaging in any transaction, practice, or course of busin=
ess which operates as a fraud or deceit upon any client or prospective clie=
nt,=E2=80=9D which is a little generic. The SEC also says that it violated =
 Rule 17a-7, which regulates trading between two different funds run by the=
 same manager, but of course the point here is that Chatham=C2=A0wasn=E2=80=
=99t=C2=A0trading directly between two of its funds =E2=80=94=C2=A0it was s=
elling to an outside broker and then buying back from that broker =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0so=C2=A0that is at least debatable.
