all spread above what it had sold the AMI Bonds to the broker the day befor=
e.=E2=80=9D=20


  [3] We=20
talked about this the other day in connection with crypto. I wrote: =E2=80=
=9CAll the downsides of stock =E2=80=94 the fiduciary duties, the sharing o=
f the value of the business, the disclosure obligations =E2=80=94 are not i=
ncidental; they are not just arbitrary punishments visited on entrepreneurs=
 who issue stock. They=E2=80=99re the point. The reason that entrepreneurs =
can raise money by issuing stock =E2=80=94 they can get real dollars in exc=
hange for pieces of paper saying =E2=80=98this is a share of a business tha=
t doesn=E2=80=99t exist yet=E2=80=99 =E2=80=94 is that there is a highly de=
veloped system of obligations that reassures investors that those pieces of=
 paper have value. The investors get some rights, some control, some econom=
ic ownership, some legal and regulatory protections, in exchange for their =
money. And that is why they are willing to part with their money.=E2=80=9D=
=20


  [4] For instance, SEC Commissioner Hester Peirce, dissenting from yesterd=
ay=E2=80=99s SPAC rules, wrote: =E2=80=9CSPACs can expand retail investment=
 opportunities by increasing the pool of companies in our public markets. A=
s many observers have noted, the number of public companies has been droppi=
ng in the United States. In 1996 there were more than 8,000 listed companie=
s on U.S. stock exchanges. In mid-2022 (the last data available), that numb=
er was just over 4,200. For context, real GDP has increased by 80% over the=
 same period. The 1990s saw an annual average of around 412 IPOs, while tha=
t average was only 248 IPOs over the last ten years. Without SPACs, the mor=
e recent annual average drops to 132 IPOs, while the 1990s average remains =
largely unchanged.=E2=80=9D


  [5] This is because technically, in a SPAC, you are going public through =
a merger with a shell company rather than through an IPO; US securities law=
s give a =E2=80=9Csafe harbor=E2=80=9D to projections for most companies, b=
ut IPO companies are excluded. Since the SPAC merger is not an IPO, it argu=
ably gets the safe harbor.


  [6] Peirce again: =E2=80=9CNot only is the Commission removing a potentia=
l avenue for bringing small companies into the public market, but it also f=
ails to acknowledge, let alone grapple with, real issues around the public =
markets=E2=80=99 accessibility for small companies. The popularity of SPACs=
 with certain types of companies was an indicator that the traditional IPO =
process was not working for these kinds of companies.=E2=80=9D


  [7] Often this is more complicated =E2=80=94 not *everyone* can trade dir=
ectly with the issuer, so you have to sell for a dollar to someone who can =
=E2=80=94 but close enough.


