10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em> Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Chatham vs. ACA</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A weird financial anomaly is that, in 2017 and=
 2018, the bonds of American Media Inc. started to trade at implausibly hig=
h prices. By late 2017, these bonds were trading at lower yields than the b=
onds of Apple Inc., implying that AMI =E2=80=94=C2=A0the small, non-investm=
ent-grade publisher of the National Enquirer =E2=80=94=C2=A0was a better cr=
edit than Apple. That seemed wrong. In 2018, AMI issued=C2=A0<em>new=C2=A0<=
/em>bonds, at a much higher yield (10.5%) than the existing bonds, which al=
so suggested that the prices of the existing bonds were wrong.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I remember that, at the time, this was a thing=
 that people talked about. Bond trading prices are public, and you could se=
e the prices of AMI bonds going crazy. Some bonds were trading at obviously=
 wrong prices, for a long time: What gave? The obvious assumption was that =
someone was doing market manipulation, and it was easy to speculate about w=
ho: Chatham Asset Management, the hedge fund firm that owned most of the bo=
nds.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It was harder to figure out=C2=A0<em>why</em>.=
 If Chatham <em>was=C2=A0</em>manipulating the market, by trading AMI bonds=
 back and forth with itself at ever-higher prices, what was it hoping to ga=
in? Surely nobody=C2=A0<em>else=C2=A0</em>would buy those bonds from Chatha=
m at the inflated prices: This is not a meme stock, it was a small market w=
ith sophisticated investors, and nobody else would just look at the tape an=
d say =E2=80=9Coh sure if these bonds trade at 110 I guess I=E2=80=99ll pay=
 110 for them.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Eventually, last April, the US Securities and =
Exchange Commission <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/34124062.285400/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyM=
y03Mg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB95c7eb4c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> brought a case</a> agai=
nst Chatham for =E2=80=9Cimproper trading of certain fixed income securitie=
s,=E2=80=9D and Chatham settled by paying $19 million. We <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34124062.285400/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmx=
vb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDQtMTAvZnR4LWxvc3QtdHJhY2stb2=
YtaXRzLW1vbmV5P2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMjUyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmd=
XRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDEyNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlz=
dHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3a988838" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked about this case=
</a> at the time, and it did provide a more or less satisfactory explanatio=
n of what was going on:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Yes, the AMI bonds were trading at si=
lly prices because someone was trading them back and forth with itself at i=
nflated prices.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Yes, it was Chatha=
m.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The=C2=A0<em>reason=C2=A0</em>f=
or this manipulation was, as these things go,=C2=A0fairly=C2=A0innocent: Ch=
atham really liked the bonds, it owned a ton of them, but it owned them in =
several different funds, and sometimes those funds saw withdrawals or bumpe=
d up against limits on how many AMI bonds they could own. Chatham=E2=80=99s=
 management loved the bonds, though, so when one of its funds had to sell t=
hem, it would sell them to another of its funds that could still hold them.=
 Each time, it would sell them at a somewhat higher price, so the price kep=
t going up. This did have the effect of making more money for Chatham (it g=
ot paid based on assets and performance, and as the bonds kept going up it =
earned about $11 million of extra fees), but that doesn=E2=80=99t seem to h=
ave been its=C2=A0<em>motivation</em>. It just liked the bonds and wanted t=
o keep them, and the most convenient way it found for keeping them was by s=
elling them to itself at ever-increasing prices.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So, right, that was an=C2=A0<em>explanation</e=
m>, but it was kind of a dumb one? It makes sense that Chatham would need t=
o sell the bonds from one fund and that it would want to buy them in anothe=
r fund. But why trade them at ever-increasing prices? That=C2=A0answer is n=
ot especially satisfying.=C2=A0The fact is that there was not much of a mar=
ket for these bonds outside of Chatham =E2=80=94=C2=A0it owned most of them=
 and mostly had to trade with itself =E2=80=94=C2=A0and so there really was=
n=E2=80=99t some easily determined fair-market value for the bonds.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So Chatham would sell the bonds to a broker,<a=
 class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpa=
rent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0and then buy them back from the broker (in a different=C2=A0fund)=
 a day or so later. The brokers=C2=A0<em>could=C2=A0</em>have tried to buy =
and sell the bonds at fair-market prices =E2=80=94=C2=A0they could have ana=
lyzed the credit and said =E2=80=9Cwell based on the trading prices of comp=
arable companies=E2=80=99 bonds, these bonds should be worth about 85 cents=
 on the dollar, so we=E2=80=99ll pay you 84.5 for them or sell to you at 85=
.5=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0but, for thinly traded risky bonds, that would h=
ave been tough, and the brokers <em>knew that Chatham would buy them back a=
nyway</em>. (Because Chatham told them it would.) So instead Chatham would =
just call a broker=C2=A0up and say =E2=80=9Chey buy these bonds from us at =
90,=E2=80=9D and the broker would, and then a day later it would call the b=
roker back and say =E2=80=9Cokay we want those bonds back, we=E2=80=99ll pa=
y you 90.5,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0so the broker could make a little commission for =
doing this.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-c=
olor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And apparently Chatham never thought to sell t=
he bonds (to itself!) for less than it paid for them: It just based each tr=
ade=E2=80=99s price on the bond=E2=80=99s trading history, which meant its =
own previous trades, which involved markups for the brokers. So=C2=A0<em>ne=
xt=C2=A0</em>time it would call the broker and sell for 90.5 and buy back f=
or 91, etc., and eventually the prices got comically high.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway this is not allowed, you are supposed t=
o trade at real market prices, etc. In some sense it is a little complicate=
d to explain=C2=A0<em>why=C2=A0</em>this is not allowed.=C2=A0The <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34124062.285400/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9maWxlcy9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2FkbWluLzIwMjMvaWEtNjI3MC5wZGY/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2cf15d04" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> SEC=E2=80=99s complaint</a> says it=
 violated rules against =E2=80=9Cengaging in any transaction, practice, or =
course of business which operates as a fraud or deceit upon any client or p=
rospective client,=E2=80=9D which is a little generic. The SEC also says th=
at it violated <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/341=
24062.285400/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L2Nmci90ZXh0LzE3LzI3MC4xN2=
EtNw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7afa1100" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Rule 17a-7</a>, which regu=
lates trading between two different funds run by the same manager, but of c=
ourse the point here is that Chatham=C2=A0<em>wasn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>trad=
ing directly between two of its funds =E2=80=94=C2=A0it was selling to an o=
utside broker and then buying back from that broker =E2=80=94=C2=A0so=C2=A0=
that is at least debatable.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in another sense =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I mean, if=
 you are trading National Enquirer bonds with yourself at a lower yield tha=
n Apple bonds, you have to know that=E2=80=99s bad, right? Again, this was =
an anomaly that=C2=A0people talked about at the time; it was obvious=C2=A0<=
em>to random bystanders=C2=A0</em>that something fishy was going on with th=
e AMI bonds. If you were=C2=A0<em>doing=C2=A0</em>the trades =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0if you were a professional hedge fund manager trading bonds with yoursel=
f at crazy prices =E2=80=94=C2=A0surely you would have noticed that they we=
re fishy? Surely you would have been like =E2=80=9Chmm is there a different=
 thing we could do?=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34124062.285400/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb=
21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDEtMjUvaGVkZ2UtZnVuZC1maWdodHMtY29t=
cGxpYW5jZS10ZWFtLWNoYXRoYW0tZGVtYW5kcy0xMDAtbWlsbGlvbi1hZnRlci1zZWMtcHJvYmU=
_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDEyNTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW=
5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMTI1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cBe546374f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Sridhar Natarajan reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Wall Street firms usually grumble in private a=
fter getting punished by regulators. Anthony Melchiorre=E2=80=99s Chatham A=
sset Management is dragging its advisers into a public legal battle for $10=
0 million.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The $6 billion hedge fund is demanding that Ad=
viser Compliance Associates not only cover Chatham=E2=80=99s costs for sett=
ling a US probe last year, but also damage to its business. In an unusual l=
awsuit, Chatham claims the outside consultant, founded by former regulators=
, failed to prevent trading practices that ran afoul of authorities. =E2=80=
=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CChatham sought, received and followed=
 advice from ACA that certain trading practices did not run afoul of the SE=
C=E2=80=99s cross-trading rules,=E2=80=9D Melchiorre, 56, said in a stateme=
nt through a spokesman. =E2=80=9CACA gave it improper advice and failed to =
flag these trades as problematic.=E2=80=9D The hedge fund intends to vigoro=
usly pursue the matter, holding ACA accountable, he said.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I=E2=80=99m torn? On the one hand, whatever yo=
ur compliance consultant does or does not tell you, if you run a hedge fund=
 and are trading bonds with yourself at increasingly irrational prices sure=
ly you can figure out that is fishy? On the other hand, if you=C2=A0<em>do=
=C2=A0</em>have a compliance consultant =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I mean, yes, fair,=
=C2=A0<em>they=C2=A0</em>should tell you that=E2=80=99s fishy? ACA says, no=
, we didn=E2=80=99t know that Chatham was setting the prices itself:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">ACA had tried to get the case thrown out. The =
investment firm is seeking =E2=80=9Cto foist blame on Adviser Compliance As=
sociates for Chatham=E2=80=99s own violations=E2=80=9D of federal securitie=
s laws and SEC rules, the consultant=E2=80=99s attorneys wrote last year in=
 their motion to dismiss the lawsuit.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC found the hedge fund and Melchiorre se=
t the prices for the trades in question, the lawyers noted. And nothing in =
the complaint =E2=80=9Calleges that Chatham ever informed ACA that it was p=
re-arranging the sales prices of the bonds, or that ACA knew of the practic=
e, much less that ACA advised Chatham to engage in it.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fine, sure. (Here are <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34124062.285400/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC=
5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JuNGVBMGxjR2pmWS92MA/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB0596243c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Chatham=E2=80=99s complaint</a>, ACA=E2=
=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34124062.2=
85400/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL=
3JtMllYbFcuSzVqMC92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb23f1301" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> motion to=
 dismiss</a>, and the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/34124062.285400/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXF=
qV0hCRmRmeElVL3I4X0M0ZzJJdzZnMC92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7f9ef235" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;"> judge=E2=80=99s ruling</a> from last month declining to dismiss the ca=
se.) But, again, ACA could see the prices! Chatham was like =E2=80=9Cit=E2=
=80=99s cool if we sell these bonds to brokers and buy them back right,=E2=
=80=9D and ACA was like =E2=80=9Csure that=E2=80=99s fine,=E2=80=9D and Cha=
tham kept doing it at insane prices and ACA kept being like =E2=80=9Ccool, =
still fine=E2=80=9D? The judge says (citations omitted):</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">According to Chatham, ACA had numerous opportu=
nities to detect and correct its error but failed to do so. For example, AC=
A conducted annual compliance program reviews and mock audits, which were i=
ntended to identify compliance issues with respect to the Investment Advise=
rs Act, the Investment Company Act, internal policies and procedures, best =
practices, and regulatory expectations. In conducting these reviews, ACA in=
terviewed employees and reviewed Chatham=E2=80=99s books and records, polic=
ies and procedures, and compliance documents. ACA also had access to Chatha=
m=E2=80=99s trading system, electronic communications, Bloomberg chats, and=
 all information it requested. Although ACA conducted these reviews in 2017=
 and 2018, it failed to flag the hundreds of Rebalancing Trades that occurr=
ed after 2016</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Likewise, ACA failed to address the Rebalancin=
g Trades in connection with the SEC examination that occurred in 2018. In M=
ay 2018, the SEC notified Chatham that it would conduct an onsite examinati=
on, and in June 2018, Chatham=E2=80=99s Chief Operating and Compliance Offi=
cer participated in a =E2=80=9Cpre-exam=E2=80=9D call with the SEC. In thes=
e communications, the SEC not only requested information and documents, but=
 also inquired into whether Chatham conducted cross trades among the funds =
its managed. The previous year, the SEC had announced that controls over cr=
oss trading was a priority for the agency. Despite this development=E2=80=
=94and despite its involvement from the outset and its participation in the=
 pre-exam call=E2=80=94ACA did not flag the Rebalancing Trades. Nor did ACA=
 address the Rebalancing Trades during the onsite examination, which ACA=E2=
=80=99s Lead Engagement Partner attended. Instead, ACA only began to scruti=
nize the Rebalancing Trades after the=C2=A0SEC requested information about =
these transactions and indicated that it would return for another onsite ex=
amination. Specifically, ACA used proprietary software to scrutinize the Re=
balancing Trades but failed to find any issues. Thus, ACA failed to prepare=
 Chatham for the subsequent onsite examination, which took place October 20=
18.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yeah I mean that does seem like bad compliance=
 consulting! Really if you are doing something obviously fishy you should j=
ust knock it off, but also, separately, if you have a compliance consultant=
,=C2=A0<em>they=C2=A0</em>should tell you to knock it off.</p>
