<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is an <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/34124062.285400/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZ=
XNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyNC05/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb6687d10" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> SEC enf=
orcement action</a> against Aon Investments USA Inc. that has the quality o=
f a nightmare. Aon acts as an adviser and consultant to the Pennsylvania Pu=
blic Employees=E2=80=99 Retirement System (PSERS), a public pension fund, a=
nd calculates the fund=E2=80=99s investment returns. PSERS asked Aon to do =
a calculation for it, based on PSERS=E2=80=99s historical returns. The deta=
ils are not that important, but if the calculation produced a number of 6.3=
6% or higher, that was good. If it produced a number lower than 6.36%, that=
 was bad, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34124062=
.285400/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9maWxlcy9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2FkbWluLzIwMjQvaWE=
tNjUzNi5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbfaa3f17" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> and</a> =E2=80=9Cp=
ublic school employees would be required to=C2=A0contribute more to the ret=
irement fund going forward.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2020, Aon did the calculation and got 6.38%=
: close to the line, but fine. But some PSERS employees noticed that =E2=80=
=9Csome of the quarterly returns in the spreadsheet provided by Aon did not=
 match the historical quarterly returns previously reported by Aon for thos=
e periods.=E2=80=9D That is a terrible thing to notice. If your client noti=
ces that some of the historical quarterly returns in your spreadsheet do no=
t match the historical quarterly returns in their spreadsheet=C2=A0=E2=80=
=94=C2=A0or, worse, in your own previous spreadsheets =E2=80=94=C2=A0then t=
he best approach is probably to delete all the spreadsheets, delete Excel, =
take a baseball bat to your computer, change your name, grow a beard, and s=
et sail for a deserted island. This is not legal or investing or consulting=
 advice but, honestly, what are the chances that you will efficiently ident=
ify and fix the source of the discrepancy? Better to start over on an islan=
d, far from any spreadsheets. Just=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/34124062.285400/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9maWxlcy9sa=
XRpZ2F0aW9uL2FkbWluLzIwMjQvaWEtNjUzNi5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCbfaa3f1=
7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">read this passage</a> and imagine being Aon Employee A:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On June 17, 2020, PSERS staff asked Aon Employ=
ee A to verify the quarterly return rates provided on the spreadsheet for f=
iscal years 2014-2017 =E2=80=9Csince some of those are significantly differ=
ent from what we have on record.=E2=80=9D About an hour later, Aon Employee=
 A responded that they =E2=80=9Cjust double checked and the quarterly retur=
ns I sent [on June 12] do match what we have in our system.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On June 19, 2020, PSERS staff asked Aon Employ=
ee A whether the discrepancies in return rates that had been identified wer=
e due to subsequent adjustments to the return rates that were reported in p=
rior quarterly reports. On the following day, Aon Employee A responded, =E2=
=80=9CI assume so, yes but I don=E2=80=99t know what historical numbers you=
=E2=80=99re referencing.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Just the worst possible emails to get. =E2=80=
=9CI assume so, yes but I don=E2=80=99t know what historical numbers you=E2=
=80=99re referencing=E2=80=9D is, in this context, a pretty good answer (no=
t legal advice, and apparently the SEC disliked it), but it would be even b=
etter to disclaim even more knowledge. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m sorry, I don=E2=
=80=99t know what historical numbers you=E2=80=99re referencing, or who you=
 are, or what a number is, or how to use email, please never contact me aga=
in.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s not going to get better. The rest of the SEC orde=
r gets worse:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Aon tries to figure out why its numbe=
rs are slightly off.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It thinks of =
promising ideas =E2=80=94=C2=A0maybe one private equity fund in the portfol=
io=C2=A0retroactively adjusted its performance reporting? =E2=80=94=C2=A0an=
d looks into them and finds out that they don=E2=80=99t explain the discrep=
ancy.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It throws out those ideas to=
 PSERS anyway to, like, suggest that it is on top of the problem? For lack =
of better ideas? Gotta say=C2=A0<em>something</em>.</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">PSERS sends around increasingly agitated letters saying t=
hings like =E2=80=9CI have been unable to locate past documentation provide=
d to the Board that would explain these reporting differences. Perhaps some=
thing has been missed, but =E2=80=A6.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"ma=
rgin-bottom: 5px;">Universal despair.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC=E2=80=99s press release says that the =
Aon partner involved =E2=80=9Cmisrepresented to PSERS that the discrepancy =
was not due to errors when, in fact, she did not know the reason for the di=
screpancy,=E2=80=9D and that =E2=80=9Cultimately, the discrepancy turned ou=
t to be due to errors in the underlying data.=E2=80=9D But the actual order=
 just sort of trails off. As far as I can tell,=C2=A0nobody ever figured ou=
t what happened:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On April 16, 2021, Aon sent an upd=
ate letter to PSERS=E2=80=99s CIO. Although the Aon Partner had given PSERS=
 the impression that Aon had identified and determined the exact cause of t=
he error, the update letter referred to Aon=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Ccontinued re=
view=E2=80=9D and indicated that =E2=80=9CAon fully understands that its re=
sponsibility to report to PSERS is ongoing and will supplement the informat=
ion related here when and to the extent appropriate and, of course, as may =
be responsive to any questions PSERS may have.=E2=80=9D The letter further =
explained that =E2=80=9Call indications are that the issues here reflect in=
advertent clerical mistakes at a data-entry level.=E2=80=9D The letter conc=
luded that =E2=80=9CAon is determined to ascertain all pertinent details su=
rrounding the issues here and will provide it as our comprehensive review c=
ontinues.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Someone just put the wrong numbers in the spre=
adsheet, somehow, at some point, probably. Nothing to be done about it. Any=
way the corrected calculation produced 6.34%, which is bad.=C2=A0</p>
