<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The central problem of securities regulation i=
s:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The lighter the regulation, the easie=
r it is for people to invest in exciting new businesses and technologies th=
at could transform the world and make them rich. (And the easier it is for =
entrepreneurs to raise money for those businesses.)</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">The lighter the regulation, the easier it is for people t=
o get ripped off by exciting new businesses and technologies that are fake =
or stupid.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s not really the case that there=E2=
=80=99s a dial you can turn between =E2=80=9CINNOVATION/FRAUD=E2=80=9D and =
=E2=80=9CNO INNOVATION/NO FRAUD,=E2=80=9D but it=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>kind=C2=
=A0</em><em>of=C2=A0</em>the case. And of course you cannot turn the dial a=
ll the way in either direction. If you want no fraud at all, you=E2=80=99ll=
 have no investment opportunities. And if you want maximum freedom for inno=
vation and fraud, then nobody will trust the market =E2=80=94=C2=A0because =
there are too many scams =E2=80=94 and it will actually be <em>harder</em> =
for companies to raise money for good ideas, and for investors to find inve=
stments.<span><a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgroun=
d-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></span></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is a widespread, though not universal, <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34124062.285400/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS92aWV3L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDQtMDQvc29tZXRoaW=
5nLWlzLWxvc3Qtd2hlbi1jb21wYW5pZXMtc3RheS1wcml2YXRlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMjUyNF9NT=
05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJt=
PTI0MDEyNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB56685dc=
8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> sense</a> that in recent years the dial for US public compani=
es maybe got turned a little too far toward NO FRAUD.<a class=3D"footnote-i=
ndex" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; dis=
play: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0I mean, there=E2=80=99s still plenty of fraud. But public compani=
es in 2024 tend to be bigger, older, more stable and more profitable than t=
hey were in 1994, and there are <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/34124062.285400/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY25uLmNvbS8yMDIzLzA2LzA5L2lud=
mVzdGluZy9wcmVtYXJrZXQtc3RvY2tzLXRyYWRpbmcvaW5kZXguaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB3618a9c3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;"> fewer of them</a>: A small (or even large) busin=
ess that would have been a viable public company a few decades ago now is m=
ore likely to stay private. This is probably partly a matter of regulatory =
changes (public-company reporting and compliance has gotten more expensive)=
, but it is also largely a matter of changes in the capital markets. The pu=
blic markets are more dominated by large institutional investors who want t=
o be able to make large investments in large companies, rather than retail =
investors who=E2=80=99d put $100 into something speculative; meanwhile much=
 more money is available in private markets, so there is less need for mids=
ize=C2=A0companies to go public.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the result is that if you are a regular pu=
blic investor it is harder than it used to be for you to buy stock in small=
, speculative companies. Those companies are now private and venture-funded=
; the public companies =E2=80=94=C2=A0the ones you can buy =E2=80=94=C2=A0a=
re bigger and more stable. Which means that you are cut off from a lot of=
=C2=A0</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">exciting, small, risky, not-yet-profit=
able companies that will turn out to be the next Amazon or Tesla, and</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">exciting, small, risky, not-yet-profit=
able frauds.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a genuine tradeoff! You might want mor=
e access to the companies at the future, even if that also=C2=A0means more =
access to frauds.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the early 2020s, special purpose acquisitio=
n companies became popular as a regulatory technology to solve this problem=
. For these purposes, the essential thing about SPACs is that they allowed =
companies to go public while marketing themselves to shareholders based on =
projections. In ordinary initial public offerings, the company will report =
its historical financial results, but will try not to put any projections o=
f future financial results in writing, because if those projections turn ou=
t to be wrong, it will get sued. The result is that it is easier to go publ=
ic via IPO if you=C2=A0<em>have=C2=A0</em>good historical financial results=
, if you=E2=80=99ve been around for a while and have profits, or at least r=
evenue.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a SPAC, however, <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34124062.285400/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMTIvbWF5YmUtc3BhY3MtYXJlLXJlYWxseS1=
pcG9zP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMjUyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdX=
JjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDEyNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB17151056" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> there is a (somewhat controversia=
l) view</a> that you can put your projections in writing and=C2=A0<em>not=
=C2=A0</em>get sued.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a> This means that a SPAC company can go around marketing itself to inves=
tors based on projections rather than on historical financials. So, say, an=
 electric-vehicle company that has never sold a car, but that has=C2=A0<em>=
big plans=C2=A0</em>to sell a billion cars a year by 2029, can tell you tha=
t. It can market based on the future rather than the past.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">(I should say that <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34124062.285400/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnL=
mNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMzEvdGhlLXNlYy1pcy1jb21pbmctZm9yLXNw=
YWNzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMjUyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJ=
jZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDEyNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8da27843" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> this difference is overstated</a>.=
 Any company doing an IPO will market itself based on projections, but the =
projections will be in roadshow meetings and analyst reports that are not f=
iled with the SEC and so not subject to lawsuits. Institutional investors w=
ill have a good sense of the company=E2=80=99s future plans, but they won=
=E2=80=99t be easily accessible to retail investors. A SPAC makes the proje=
ctions more accessible, including to retail investors.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The obvious result is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">SPACs let more exciting early-stage, =
speculative, pre-revenue companies go public; and</li>=09<li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">A=C2=A0<em>lot=C2=A0</em>of those projections <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34124062.285400/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTAtMDMvdGhlLXNlYy1oYWQtYS=
1idXN5LXdlZWs_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDEyNTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1d=
G1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMTI1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0=
dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7f9ece5b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> turn out to be wildly infl=
ated</a>, and SPAC investors lose money when those companies fail.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Again: a tradeoff! One that you might be fine =
with! Or not.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From a market perspective, the market was pret=
ty comfortable with this during a boom in private tech startup valuations: =
When everyone wanted to get access to speculative tech companies, SPAC inve=
stors also wanted that. And then when that boom ended and a lot of SPAC com=
panies collapsed, the market stopped being comfortable: When SPAC investors=
 were repeatedly burned, they stopped buying SPACs. Circle of life.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From a regulatory perspective, though, the cur=
rent US Securities and Exchange Commission <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/34124062.285400/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS=
9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMTMvZ3JhYi1zcGFjLW1lZ2EtbWVyZ2VyLWlzbi10L=
W1lZ2Etd2l0aG91dC1ibGFja3JvY2stcGlwZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTI1MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1=
dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAxMjUmdXR=
tX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2c0f92f6" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> ha=
s never really liked SPACs</a>, and yesterday it <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34124062.285400/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9u=
ZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyNC04/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB77efc402" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>adopted new rules</a> regulating them. The rules require various new discl=
osures about the conflicts of interest and other <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34124062.285400/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMDkvc3BhYy1tYXRoLW5vLWxvbmdlci1hZGR=
zLXVwP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMjUyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdX=
JjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDEyNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4d76cf82" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> investor-unfriendly features</a> =
of SPACs, but the big thing is that =E2=80=9Cthe rules make the Private Sec=
urities Litigation Reform Act of 1995 safe harbor from liability for forwar=
d-looking statements unavailable to certain blank check companies, includin=
g SPACs.=E2=80=9D So now, if you market a SPAC based on projections, you=C2=
=A0<em>can=C2=A0</em>get sued, just like in an IPO.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I assume that this will be bad for the SPAC ma=
rket going forward, though I don=E2=80=99t really know. (The SPAC market is=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34124062.285400/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9maW5hbmNlL3JlZ3VsYXRpb24vc2VjLXdhbnRzLXRvLW1ha2Ut=
c3VyZS1zcGFjLWludmVzdG9ycy1rbm93LXdoYXQtdGhleXJlLWdldHRpbmctaW50by01MTBhY2E=
zMD9tb2Q9aXRwX3dzag/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc4c92486" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> pretty dorm=
ant right now</a> anyway.) Perhaps it will adapt, and SPACs will be another=
 technology (like IPOs and direct listings) for taking companies public; pe=
rhaps it will evolve into things like <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/34124062.285400/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGl=
uaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTEtMjkvYmlsbC1hY2ttYW4taGFzLWEtc3BhcmM_Y21waWQ9Qk=
JEMDEyNTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0Z=
XImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMTI1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cBcb71643e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;"> Bill Ackman=E2=80=99s SPARC</a>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But whether or not SPACs survive as a technolo=
gy, yesterday the SEC killed them as a regulatory arbitrage: SPACs are no l=
onger a way to go public based on projections (without getting sued). They =
are no longer a way for regular retail investors to access a different=C2=
=A0<em>type=C2=A0</em>of company, the small, risky, speculative kind, the k=
ind that is either exciting or doomed.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#=
footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: no=
ne !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-bl=
ock;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a></p>
