<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way the stablecoin business works is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You send $1 to a company (the stablec=
oin issuer), and it sends you back a token representing =E2=80=9Cone dollar=
, but on the blockchain.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=
If you want your dollar back, you can (probably) give the issuer back the t=
oken and get back the dollar.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-=
7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !impor=
tant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The issuer invests your dollar an=
d earns interest.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a zero-interest-rate environment, the issue=
r didn=E2=80=99t earn much interest, but it earned some, and it kept it: Yo=
u were so grateful to be able to hold a dollar on the blockchain, and rates=
 were so low, that you didn=E2=80=99t worry about earning interest. (Also, =
when crypto was booming,=C2=A0you could invest your stablecoin into some cr=
ypto lending protocol that would probably pay you 20% interest, so the <em>=
issuer=C2=A0</em>didn=E2=80=99t need to pay you anything.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a 5% interest-rate environment, the issuer =
earns way more interest, but it=E2=80=99s awkward for them not to pay you a=
ny. You can get 4% or 5% interest in an insured bank or a regulated money-m=
arket fund; why should you get zero from some weird crypto startup?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You might expect there to be a straightforward=
 market-driven move to stablecoin issuers paying interest, but there are co=
mplications. One is that stablecoins are largely=C2=A0<em>trading=C2=A0</em=
>instruments, tools for trading crypto and making payments, and so liquidit=
y and usefulness are more important than yield. The biggest stablecoins (Te=
ther, etc.) have the most liquidity and utility, so crypto traders are not =
going to abandon them for some smaller weirder tokens that pay interest, so=
 there=E2=80=99s not much pressure on them to pay anything.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other complication is that a stablecoin th=
at pays interest is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/34124062.285400/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzL=
